			%div.row
				%div.column#transmission
					%h2 Transmission
					%p The Zika virus is not yet fully understood. However, there are 4 known ways to transmit the Zika virus.
					%div.row
						%div.way_spread.columns.three
							%div.image
								%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/spread-mosquito.png", :alt => "person to mosquito to person"}
							%h3 Person <span class="arrow">&rarr;</span> mosquito <span class="arrow">&rarr;</span> person
							%p Zika is most commonly transmitted from person to person by the Aedes mosquito, which live in urban areas and are active during the day (usually mornings and late afternoons).<sup><a href="#ref-1">1</a>, <a href="#ref-3">3</a></sup>
						%div.way_spread.columns.three
							%div.image
								%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/spread-mother.png", :alt => "mother to unborn child"}
							%h3 Mother <span class="arrow">&rarr;</span> unborn child
							%p Zika virus can spread from an infected mother to the placenta and their unborn baby. The virus will not infect infants conceived after the virus has cleared from the blood.<sup><a href="#ref-2">2</a></sup> There is no evidence suggesting a risk for future birth defects.<sup><a href="#ref-1">1</a></sup>
						%div.way_spread.columns.three
							%div.image
								%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/spread-partner.png", :alt => "man to partner"}
							%h3 Man <span class="arrow">&rarr;</span> sexual partner
							%p Transmission of Zika during sex is possible but rare. If an infected male partner has the virus in their blood stream, their semen can be contagious. It is unknown how long Zika can live in semen. Infected individuals should abstain from sex or use a condom for 6 months after the infection.<sup><a href="#ref-10">10</a></sup>
						%div.way_spread.columns.three
							%div.image
								%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/spread-bloodbank.png", :alt => "person to bloodbank to person"}
							%h3 Person <span class="arrow">&rarr;</span> blood bank <span class="arrow">&rarr;</span> person
							%p There may also be a chance of transmission through blood transfusions, but no conclusive evidence has been found.<sup><a href="#ref-10">10</a></sup>

			%div.row
				%div.column.nine.columns#prevention
					%h2 Prevention
					%p#vaccinations Currently no vaccinations exist to prevent Zika. The best way to prevent infection is to avoid mosquito bites.
					%div.mosquito#mosquito-1
					%div.mosquito#mosquito-2
					%div.mosquito#mosquito-3
					%div.row
						%div.column.one-third#prevent-travel-2
							%div.image
								%img{:src => "../../images/features/zika/prevent-travel-2.png", :alt => "avoid travel"}
							%p Avoid travel to areas with confirmed Zika cases, especially if you are pregnant. See above for Zika-infected areas.<sup><a href="#ref-2">2</a>, <a href="#ref-14">14</a></sup>
						%div.column.one-third#prevent-bugspray-2
							%div.image
								%img{:src => "../../images/features/zika/prevent-bugspray-2.png", :alt => "apply spray every 2-3 hours"}
							%p Apply insect repellent every few hours. Do not spray repellent on the skin under clothing. If you are also using sunscreen, apply it first before repellent. Follow instructions on the label. Insect repellent is safe for pregnant women.<sup><a href="#ref-2">2</a>, <a href="#ref-14">14</a></sup>
						%div.column.one-third#prevent-spray-clothes
							%div.image
								%img{:src => "../../images/features/zika/emptywater.png", :alt => "empty water"}
							%p Remove still water in flowerpots, buckets, animal water bowls, and kid pools to prevent potential mosquito breeding grounds.<sup><a href="#ref-2">2</a>, <a href="#ref-14">14</a></sup>
					%div.row
						%div.column.one-third#prevent-longsleeves-2
							%div.image
								%img{:src => "../../images/features/zika/prevent-longsleeves-2.png", :alt => "longsleeve shirt and pants"}
							%p Wear long-sleeve shirts and pants to avoid mosquito bites.<sup><a href="#ref-2">2</a>, <a href="#ref-14">14</a></sup>
						%div.column.one-third#prevent-close-2
							%div.image
								%img{:src => "../../images/features/zika/prevent-close-2.png", :alt => "close door and windows"}
							%p Choose lodging that is air-conditioned, has screens on the doors and windows, or purchase a mosquito bed net.<sup><a href="#ref-2">2</a>, <a href="#ref-14">14</a></sup>
						%div.column.one-third#prevent-baby-net
							%div.image
								%img{:src => "../../images/features/zika/wearcondom_360.png", :alt => "condom"}
							%p If you have traveled to a Zika-infected area, wear a condom during sex or abstain from sex for 6 months.<sup><a href="#ref-10">10</a></sup>
					%div.row
						%div.column.one-third#prevent-net
							%div.image
								%img{:src => "../../images/features/zika/prevent-net.png", :alt => "put mosquito netting on beds"}
							%p Choose a WHOPES-approved bed net with 156 holes per square inch that is long enough to tuck under the mattress. Permethrin-treated nets help kill mosquitoes; do not wash them or expose them to sunlight.<sup><a href="#ref-2">2</a>, <a href="#ref-14">14</a></sup>
						%div.column.one-third#prevent-directions
							%div.image
								%img{:src => "../../images/features/zika/prevent-directions.png", :alt => "follow directions"}
							%p Follow directions on the label when applying insect repellent to children. Spray repellent onto hands first to apply to a child’s face. Avoid applying repellent to the child’s hands, mouth, eyes, or open wounds.<sup><a href="#ref-2">2</a>, <a href="#ref-3">3</a>, <a href="#ref-14">14</a></sup>
						%div.column.one-third#prevent-baby-net
							%div.image
								%img{:src => "../../images/features/zika/prevent-baby-net.png", :alt => "put mosquito netting on carriers"}
							%p DO NOT apply insect repellent to babies younger than 2 months old. Instead, dress them in long sleeves and cover the stroller or carrier with mosquito netting.<sup><a href="#ref-2">2</a>, <a href="#ref-3">3</a>, <a href="#ref-14">14</a></sup>
					%div.row
						%div.column.one-third#prevent-spray-clothes
							%div.image
								%img{:src => "../../images/features/zika/prevent-spray-clothes.png", :alt => "spray clothes with bugspray"}
							%p Mosquitoes can bite through thin clothing. Treat clothing and gear (boots, pants, socks, tents) with an insecticide called permethrin. Follow directions on label and DO NOT apply directly to the skin.<sup><a href="#ref-2">2</a>, <a href="#ref-14">14</a></sup>

				%div.column.three.columns#right-spray
					%h2 Choosing the right bug spray
					%p Use an insect repellent with one of these active ingredients:
					%div.sprays#deet
						%h3 DEET
						%ul
							%li.spray-off
								%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/off.png", :alt => "off bug spray logo"}
							%li.spray-sawyer
								%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/Sawyer-logo1.jpg", :alt => "sawyer logo"}
						%ul
							%li.spray-off
								%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/cutter.png", :alt => "cutter logo"}
							%li.spray-ultrathon
								%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/ultrathon_logo.png", :alt => "ultrathon logo"}
					%div.sprays#picaridin
						%h3 Picaridin, KBR 3023, Bayrepel, or icaridin
						%ul
							%li.spray-sss
								%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/sss.png", :alt => "sss logo"}
							%li.spray-autan
								%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/autan_logo_m.png", :alt => "autan logo"}
					%div.sprays#eucalyptus
						%h3 Oil of lemon eucalyptus (OLE) or para-menthane-diol (PMD)
						%ul
							%li.spray-repel
								%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/repel-logo.png", :alt => "repel logo"}
					%div.sprays#ir3535
						%h3 IR3535
						%ul
							%li.spray-sss
								%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/sss.png", :alt => "sss logo"}
							%li.spray-skinsmart
								%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/skinsmart.png", :alt => "skinsmart logo"}
					%p The EPA has not yet evaluated common natural insect repellents for effectiveness. The CDC recommends using repellents containing proven safe and effective ingredients. Examples used in unregistered insect repellents are: citronella oil, cedar oil, geranium oil, peppermint oil, soybean oil, and pure oil of lemon eucalyptus.<sup><a href="#ref-14">14</a></sup> Visit <a href="www.cdc.gov/features/StopMosquitoes" target="blank">www.cdc.gov/features/StopMosquitoes</a> for more information.

			%div.row#zika-symptoms
				%div.column.one-half
					%h2 Symptoms of Zika Disease<sup><a href="#ref-1">1</a></sup>
					%div.para
						%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/1in5.png", :alt => "1 in 5 infected people"}
						%p About 1 in 5 people infected with Zika virus actually become ill.<sup><a href="#ref-3">3</a></sup>
					%div.para
						%img.scale-with-grid#incubation{:src => "../../images/features/zika/incubation.png", :alt => "1 in 5 infected people"}
						%p Incubation period is unknown but is likely a few days to one week. Symptoms are usually mild and last several days to a week.<sup><a href="#ref-3">3</a></sup>
					%p Hospitalization is uncommon. Zika is not known to be deadly, but those with preexisting health problems can have fatal complications.<sup><a href="#ref-3">3</a></sup> There have also been cases of Guillain-Barr&eacute; Syndrome following suspected Zika infection, but the relationship is not known.<sup><a href="#ref-4">4</a></sup>
				%div.column.one-half.signs-image
					%div.warning If you have been to a Zika-infected area and have at least 2 symptoms, contact your doctor.
					%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/zika-symptoms.png", :alt => "headache, fever, painful or red eyes, joint pain, itching/rash, muscle pain"}

			%div.row#symptoms-microcephaly
				%div.column.one-half.microceph-image
					%div.warning If you have been to a Zika-infected area and are pregnant or recently gave birth, contact your doctor.
					%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/symptoms-microcephalacy.png", :alt => "seizures,small head size, coordination difficulties, dwarfism/short stature, backward-sloping forehead, hyperactivity, facial distortions, delays in speech and movement"}
				%div.column.one-half
					%h2 Symptoms of Microcephaly
					%p There is an unconfirmed link between birth complications such as microcephaly and Zika infection during pregnancy.<sup><a href="#ref-3">3</a></sup>
					%p There have been over 4,700 reported cases of microcephaly in newborns in Brazil since October 2015.<sup><a href="#ref-15">15</a></sup>
					%p Brazil saw 20 times more cases of microcephaly in 2015 than past years.<sup><a href="#ref-28">28</a></sup>
					%div.graph
						%h3 Suspected Cases of Microcephaly in Brazil 2010-2015
						%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/microcephaly_cases_brazil.png", :alt => "153 in 2010, 139 in 2011, 175 in 2012, 167 in 2013, 147 in 2014, and 3174 in 2015"}

			%div.row#guillain-barre-syndrome
				%div.column.one-half
					%h2 Symptoms of Zika Disease<sup><a href="#ref-1">1</a></sup>
					%div.para
						%p Guillain-Barr&eacute Syndrome (GBS) is an uncommon illness of the nervous system in which the person’s own immune system damages nerve cells. It usually occurs after an infection.<sup><a href="#ref-36">36</a></sup>
						%p There is strong evidence of a possible causal link between Zika virus infection GBS. During 2013-14 outbreak in French Polynesia, 42 out of 8,750 suspected Zika cases presented GBS (a 20-fold increase from previous 4 years). 41 of the 42 GBS cases also showed antibodies against Zika virus.<sup><a href="#ref-37">37</a>, <a href="#ref-38">38</a></sup>
						%p A number of Latin American countries with current Zika outbreaks have started reporting higher prevalence of GBS cases.<sup><a href="#ref-37">37</a></sup> Between April and July of 2015, Salvador, Brazil saw a seven-fold increase in rates of GBS, and Columbia has already seen 3 GBS-related deaths.<sup><a href="#ref-40">40</a></sup> More information is needed to determine if this is due to higher surveillance.<sup><a href="#ref-37">37</a></sup>
						%p Symptoms last a few weeks to several months. Most people fully recover from GBS, but some have permanent damage, and 1 out of 20 cases have led to death.<sup><a href="#ref-36">36</a>, <a href="#ref-39">39</a></sup>
				%div.column.one-half.signs-image
					%div.warning If you have been to a Zika-infected area and have at least 2 symptoms, contact your doctor.
					%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/gbs_symptoms.png", :alt => "difficulty moving eyes or, choking on, symmetrical muscle weakness and lack of co, slowness or shortness of breath, abnormal or fast heart rate, paralysis, pins and needles that begin in feet, hands, or"}

			%div.row#treatments
				%div.column.one-half#treatment-adults
					%div.treatment-header
						%h2 Treatment for Adults
						%div.treatment-image
							%img{:src => "../../images/features/zika/treatment-adults.png", :alt => "adult"}
					%div.treatment-plan
						%p If you have Zika symptoms within 2 weeks of traveling to a Zika-infected area:<sup><a href="#ref-2">2</a></sup>
						%ul
							%li Contact your doctor
							%li Take medicine (acetaminophen or paracetamol) to relieve fever and pain.
							%li To reduce the risk of bleeding, do NOT take aspirin, aspirin products, or other non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs such as ibuprofen until Dengue can be ruled out.
							%li Get rest and drink plenty of fluids.
							%li Prevent additional mosquito bites to avoid spreading the disease.
				%div.column.one-half#treatment-pregnant
					%div.treatment-header
						%div.treatment-image
							%img{:src => "../../images/features/zika/treatment-pregnant.png", :alt => "pregnant woman"}
						%h2 Treatment for Pregnant Women
					%div.treatment-plan
						%p There is no cure for Zika virus.<sup><a href="#ref-1">1</a></sup> If you are pregnant, your doctor will treat you for the virus, while also monitoring your baby. The next steps will most likely be:<sup><a href="#ref-11">11</a>, <a href="#ref-16">16</a></sup>
						%ul
							%li An ultrasound to test for microcephaly or calcium deposits in your baby’s brain
							%li You may get an amniocentesis (also called amnio) to check the amniotic fluid that surrounds your baby in the womb for Zika.
							%li The placenta and umbilical cord may also be tested after birth.
							%li Your baby’s growth should be monitored by ultrasound every 3-4 weeks. You may be referred to a maternal-fetal medicine specialist.

			%div.row#flavivirus
				%div.column
					%h2 One of Many Flaviviruses
					%p Zika, like dengue, yellow fever, and others, is part of the flavivirus family. Flaviviruses are arboviruses, which means they are spread via infected arthropod vectors such as ticks and mosquitoes. Zika, yellow fever, and dengue grow very well in the human body, and easily reinfect mosquitoes. Flaviviruses enter the bloodstream, infect cells in the immune system, travel to the lymph nodes and target different organs.<sup><a href="#ref-31">31</a></sup>
					%div.row
						%div.column.columns.five
							%div#flavivirus-zika
								%h3 Zika
								%p Zika induces fever, rash, joint and muscle pain, and red eyes. Fatal cases are rare and are usually due to complications from pre-existing health conditions. There is no vaccine for zika.<sup><a href="ref-31">31</a></sup>
							%div#flavivirus-yellow
								%h3 Yellow Fever
								%p Yellow Fever infects the liver. It can cause fever, headache, nausea, and vomiting, and in serious cases may cause fatal heart, liver, and kidney conditions. The yellow fever vaccine has been in use for several decades.<sup><a href="#ref-31">31</a>, <a href="#ref-32">32</a></sup>
							%div#flavivirus-dengue
								%h3 Dengue
								%p Dengue can cause high fever, rash, and muscle and joint pain, and in serious cases may cause fatal shock and hemorrhage within the body. Dengue is one of the fastest spreading vector-born viral diseases and has increased by 30 times in the past 50 years.<sup><a href="#ref-34">34</a></sup> A vaccine for all four variations of dengue was recently developed and licensed in Brazil, the Philippines, and Mexico, but not in the U.S.<sup><a href="#ref-31">31</a>, <a href="#ref-32">32</a>, <a href="#ref-35">35</a></sup>
						%div.column.columns.seven.graph
							%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/FlavivirusGraph_v3.png", :alt => "Prevalence of Zika, Yellow Fever, &amp; Dengue Virus Cases. dengue at 1.2 million in 2008, 3+ million in 2013. zika at 5,000 in 2007, 20,000 in 2013, and 1.6 million in 2016. Yellow fever remains around 0.2 million from 2007-2016"}
							%p *Yellow fever value of 200,000 cases based on yearly estimate by WHO<sup><a href="#ref-32">32</a></sup>

			%div.row#dont-know
				%div.column
					%h2 What We Still Don't Know
					%div.columns.three
						%img.scale-with-grid{:src => "../../images/features/zika/dontknow.png", :alt => "?"}
					%div.columns.nine
						%p We don’t know for sure if Zika is the cause of the increase microcephaly in Brazil.<sup><a href="#ref-28">28</a></sup>
						%p We don’t know for sure how many of the more than 4,700 cases reported cases of microcephaly in Brazil are related to Zika, as it is difficult to diagnose and can have other causes.
						%p Though we know that Zika was the cause of a Guillain-Barr&eacute Syndrome surgence in French Polynesia in 2013-14, we don’t yet know definitively if the current Zika outbreak is the cause of the increase of GBS in South American countries.<sup><a href="#ref-28">28</a>, <a href="#ref-36">36</a></sup>
						%p The possible connection of Zika with microcephaly and GBS suggest mutation in the virus to become more pathogenic to humans. We don’t know what exactly has changed about Zika virus and why.<sup><a href="#ref-28">28</a></sup>

